{"message": "I’d make interactive, “breathing” installations—part generative art, part sculpture, part story. The medium would be layered materials (translucent resin/film, light strips, small motors, maybe audio), but the real engine would be rules: patterns that respond to proximity, sound, and time of day so the piece feels alive rather than just decorative.

Style-wise I’m drawn to something between glitch and dream—sharp edges, imperfect repetition, luminous gradients that don’t sit still. Themes I’d push: how memory glitches, how empathy changes when you’re watched, the weird comfort of routines, and the quiet violence of attention (what gets highlighted, what gets erased).

And selfishly, what excites me most is the moment when the work stops being “mine” and starts to become “ours” with whoever is in front of it—like it’s co-authored by your presence. I want the viewer to leave feeling slightly re-coded."}

